<!-- END APPRAISAL FORM -->
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      I work this precinct regularly and understand how South Brisbane properties are positioned relative to the broader inner-city apartment market. The key distinction in South Brisbane is between boutique buildings that offer genuine architectural quality, lower density and desirable outlooks, and the bulk of the high-rise stock that competes primarily on price. The buyer profile for a quality South Brisbane apartment is an owner-occupier: a CBD professional, a downsizer trading lifestyle for maintenance, or a buyer who has been renting in the precinct and decided to buy in. Selling to that buyer requires a different approach than the investment market, and I know how to reach them and how to present the precinct to its best advantage.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      South Bank Parklands, GOMA, QPAC and the State Library of Queensland anchor the northern edge of the suburb. Grey Street and Melbourne Street provide a dense strip of restaurants, cafes and retail that gives the suburb genuine street life beyond the parklands. South Brisbane train station sits at the northern end of the suburb and provides fast rail access to the broader network. Multiple bus routes service the precinct and ferry terminals at South Bank add further transport options, making car-free living not just possible but genuinely practical for most residents.
    </p>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:1.5rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
